Japanese, Australian Stock Futures Drop Amid Continuing Violence in Libya

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-03-09T23:01:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-09/japanese-australian-stock-futures-drop-amid-continuing-violence-in-libya.html
Japanese and Australian  stock
futures  declined as violence in  Libya  tempered optimism in a
global economic recovery. Australian futures were little changed.  American depositary receipts of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial
Group Inc., Japan’s biggest publicly traded bank, fell 0.8
percent from the closing share price in Tokyo. Those of Toyota
Motor Corp., an automaker that earns about 70 percent of its
revenue abroad, slid 0.3 percent. ADRs of BHP Billiton Ltd., the
world’s largest mining company and Australia’s No. 1 oil
producer, dropped 0.8 percent from the closing price in Sydney.  “Libya is chaotic and a sense of uncertainty for the
future is increasing even in countries surrounding Libya,” said
Mitsushige Akino, who oversees about $450 million in Tokyo at
Ichiyoshi Investment Management Co.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
March closed at 10,560 in  Chicago  yesterday, compared with
10,600 in  Osaka , Japan. Futures on Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index
retreated 0.1 percent.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. The index dropped 0.1 percent yesterday in  New
York , falling for a third time in four days.  Libyan leader  Muammar Qaddafi ’s forces carried out air and
artillery strikes on central oil facilities as the government
posted a 500,000 dinar ($407,000) reward for anyone who arrests
the head of the rebel leadership council.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index rose 0.5 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with gains of 5 percent by the S&P
500 and 1.9 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Shares in the
Asian benchmark were valued at 13.9 times estimated earnings on
average as of the last close, compared with 13.7 times for the
S&P 500 and 11.2 times for the Stoxx 600.  Japan’s Cabinet office is scheduled to announce the
nation’s gross domestic product for the fourth quarter at 8:50
a.m. in Tokyo. The median forecast of 26 economists surveyed by
Bloomberg News was for a 1.2 percent annual drop.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Norie Kuboyama in Tokyo at 
